=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Rule of 3?

Answer:
If a class defines either destructor, copy constructor, or copy
assignment operator, it usually needs to define all three.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Why is Rule of 3 needed?

Answer:
To avoid shallow copy problems like:

• Double delete
• Dangling pointers
• Memory corruption

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. What problem does Rule of 3 solve?

Answer:
Resource ownership issues.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. What is shallow copy?

Answer:
Copying pointer values only.

Both objects point to same memory.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. What is deep copy?

Answer:
Allocating new memory and copying contents.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Why return *this from assignment operator?

Answer:
Supports chaining.

s1 = s2 = s3;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Why check:

if (this != &other)

Answer:
To avoid self-assignment problems.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Rule of 3 states that if a class manages a resource and defines a
destructor, copy constructor, or copy assignment operator, then it
should usually define all three. This is required because the compiler's
default copy operations perform shallow copies, which can lead to
double deletion and resource corruption. Implementing all three ensures
proper resource ownership through deep copying.

